description:
The Director of Construction and Field Operations is responsible for managing all construction activities (new construction, rehabilitation and repair projects, Aging in Place, ramps and interior retrofitting) including project planning and budgeting, managing and coordinating the construction team including Habitat staff, volunteers, subcontractors, design professionals, city inspectors, scheduling projects, bidding of labor and materials, and managing the construction warehouse. The Director of Construction and Field Operations will manage and supervise the Construction Supervisor(s) and Project Manager(s).

Duties + Responsibilities

* Work with the Executive Director (ED), Director of Finance and Project Manager on budget
* planning and implementation;
* Develop and maintain construction budgets and schedules;
* Develop and manage a construction contract and material bid system;
* Monitor budget to actuals expenses on all projects;
* Monitor invoices against compliance with the budget;
* Review and approve with the ED all construction contracts;
* Manage, with the administrative staff, In-Kind solicitations of building material and labor donations;
* Lead weekly construction staff meetings;
* Monitor construction quality and specification compliance;
* Minimum weekly visits to each construction site;
* Coordinate with site supervision and staff for special events;
* Keep the construction department up to date on changing HFHI and Building Code requirements;
* Hold quarterly safety training sessions and schedule safety training classes for certification;
* Provide for construction site orientation for new hires/volunteers;
* Manage and supervise Construction Superintendents through the duration of the projects;
* Set goals with each member of the construction department;
* With Executive Director, conduct annual reviews on construction staff performance;
* Communicate safety procedures to all construction staff including enforcement;
* Assist ED in developing and implementing project schedule, provide project reports, including weekly updates, and perform any necessary field paperwork as required;
* Assist with hiring department employees;
* Oversee all proposals, contracts, invoices and payments for all projects;
* Work closely with the administrative staff for construction materials and service donations;
* Participate in Construction Committee;
* Maintain order, inventory, and upkeep of construction warehouse;
* Represent Monmouth County Habitat for Humanity at events, and attend conferences/trainings as needed, support the mission and programs of Monmouth County Habitat for Humanity; and
* Other duties as assigned.

Qualifications

* Minimum of 5 years of experience in residential construction planning and development;
* Thorough knowledge of all aspects of construction technology, equipment, and methods;
* Proven success in all phases of new and rehab construction processes;
* Must be able to appropriately communicate with a diverse range of people and groups and

remain consistent in keeping a professional demeanor at all times;

* Excellent verbal and written communication skills; and
* Excellent interpersonal skills.

Required Skills/Knowledge/Abilities

* Ability to manage multiple projects, develop new programs, organize work, set priorities, and manage deadlines and shifting priorities;
* Ability to train, supervise and evaluate a range of personnel who perform a variety of trades;
* Consistently provides clear, timely direction and takes the time to listen;
* Ability to use positive and supportive strategies to achieve success and lead by example;
* Open and welcoming of people of any faith or no faith, individuals of diverse populations, and socio-economic backgrounds; and
* Demonstrates a high level of ethics, integrity, diplomacy and initiative.

Other Requirements

* Driver’s license with excellent record;
* Ability to operate company vehicles, construction tools and equipment;
* Physical demands: Strenuous activity requiring ability to sit, walk, carry, push, pull, lift 50 lbs.,

climb and bend;

* Working conditions: Exposure to extreme temperatures, loud noises, and other various adverse working conditions associated with construction and outdoor work;
* Ability to pass criminal background screening as required by Habitat for Humanity International.

Note The above list of duties while specific to the position is not exhaustive. The primary responsibility of the position is to direct the construction department and assist the affiliate in achieving annual goals. Therefore, it is possible that responsibilities may change and increase as deemed necessary to accomplish that task.

Job Conditions Position is full time (minimum 40 hours per week) and works Monday through Friday and evening and weekend work as required. It is an exempt position. Conditions and benefits are contained in the board approved Employee Policies and Procedures Manual.

Job Type: Full-time

Pay: $70,000.00 - $85,000.00 per year

Benefits:

* 401(k)
* Health savings account
* Life insurance
* Paid time off

Schedule:

* Day shift
* Monday to Friday

Experience:

* Construction: 1 year (Preferred)
* Residential construction: 1 year (Preferred)

License/Certification:

* Driver's License (Preferred)

Willingness to travel:

* 25% (Preferred)

Work Location: On the road

